  <\section>
    \ Semantic Entailment
  </section>

  How to prove that an argument is valid, that is the set of premisessemantically entails (可推导) the conclusion?

  <subsection|Satisfiability of a set of formulas(可满足性)>

  let <math|\<Sigma\>\<subseteq\>Form<around*|(|\<cal*-L\><rsup|p>|)>>.v is a truth valuation.Define:

  <\align>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|\<Sigma\>>|<cell|=<choice|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|1,if for each B\<in\>\<Sigma\>,B<rsup|v>=1>>|<row|<cell|0,else>>>>>>>>>
  </align>

  <math|\<Sigma\>> is a satisfiable iff there is some valuation v such that <math|\<Sigma\><rsup|v>=1>;we say v satisfies <math|\<Sigma\>>.

  存在真值指派v使得命题组<math|\<Sigma\>>的所有命题为真，则称该命题组<math|\<Sigma\>>为可满足的，v满足了<math|\<Sigma\>>。

  <subsection|logical consequence(逻辑推论)<math|\<Sigma\>\<vDash\>A>>

  Let \<Sigma\> be a set of formulas (\<Sigma\> \<subseteq\> Form(<math|\<cal*-L\><rsup|p>> )), A be a formula (A \<in\> Form(<math|\<cal*-L\><rsup|p>> )).

  A is a logical consequence(逻辑推论) of <math|\<Sigma\>>, or <math|\<Sigma\>> (semantically) entails (逻辑蕴含) A, or <math|\<Sigma\>\<vDash\>A>

  if and only if : for all v, if <math|\<Sigma\><rsup|v>=1>, then <math|A<rsup|v>=1>.

  显然，这要求<math|\<Sigma\>>是可满足的。

  在应用中，<math|\<Sigma\>一般代表前提，A一般代表推论>，<math|\<Sigma\>\<vDash\>A>指当前提条件都成立，那么推论也成立。

  <subsection|How to prove <math|\<Sigma\>\<vDash\>A>>

  <\itemize>
    <item>Direct Prove
  </itemize>

  Find all v such that <math|\<Sigma\><rsup|v>=1>, show that <math|A<rsup|v>=1>。

  You can choose using a truth table.

  <\example>
    \;

    Prove {\<neg\>p} \<vDash\> (p\<wedge\>\<neg\>q \<rightarrow\> p\<wedge\>q)

    <\proof>
      \;

      <block|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|p>|<cell|q>|<cell|<math|\<neg\>q>>|<cell|<math|p\<wedge\>\<neg\>q>>|<cell|<math|p\<wedge\>q>>|<cell|A=p\<wedge\>\<neg\>q \<rightarrow\> p\<wedge\>q>|<cell|<math|\<Sigma\>>={<math|\<neg\>>p}>>|<row|1|<cell|1>|<cell|0>|<cell|0>|<cell|1>|<cell|1>|<cell|0>>|<row|<cell|1>|<cell|0>|<cell|1>|<cell|1>|<cell|0>|<cell|0>|<cell|0>>|<row|<cell|0>|<cell|1>|<cell|0>|<cell|0>|<cell|0>|<cell|1>|<cell|1>>|<row|<cell|0>|<cell|0>|<cell|1>|<cell|0>|<cell|0>|<cell|1>|<cell|1>>>>>

      \;
    </proof>

    \;
  </example>

  <\itemize>
    <item>Proof by contradiction
  </itemize>

  <\example>
    Prove {A \<rightarrow\> B, B \<rightarrow\> C} \<vDash\> A \<rightarrow\> C

    <\proof>
      \;

      if the hypothesis is not true,

      there exist a valuation v, such that:

      <math|<around*|(|A \<rightarrow\> B|)><rsup|v>>=1,<math|<around*|(|B \<rightarrow\> C|)><rsup|v>>=1,<math|<around*|(|A\<rightarrow\>C|)><rsup|v>=0>

      then it must have

      <math|A<rsup|v>>=0 and <math|C<rsup|v>=1> from <math|<around*|(|A\<rightarrow\>C|)><rsup|v>=0>

      then it can be imply that <math|B<rsup|v>>=0 from <math|<around*|(|A \<rightarrow\> B|)><rsup|v>>=1

      but now <math|<around*|(|B \<rightarrow\> C|)><rsup|v>>=0, that lead to a contradictory.

      \;
    </proof>
  </example>

  \;

  <\itemize>
    <item>Proof System (will be discussed in the following lessons)
  </itemize>

  <subsection|Application of logical consequence>

  <\example>
    “If I'm guilty, I must be punished; I'm guilty. Thus I must be punished.”\ 

    Define p=I'm guilty,q=I must be punished;

    <\align>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<around*|{|p\<rightarrow\>q,p|}>\<vDash\>q>|<cell|>>>>
    </align>
  </example>

  <\example>
    “If I'm guilty, I must be punished; I'm not guilty. Thus I must not be punished.”

    Define p=I'm guilty,q=I must be punished; The statement is wrong because:

    <\align>
      <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<around*|{|p\<rightarrow\>q,\<neg\>p|}>\<nvDash\>\<neg\>q>|<cell|>>|<row|<cell|<around*|(|p<rsup|v>=0,q<rsup|v>=1|)>>|<cell|>>>>
    </align>
  </example>

  <section|Properties of Logical Consequence>

  <\theorem>
    Logical Equivalence

    Suppose <math|A\<in\>Form<around*|(|\<cal*-L\><rsup|p>|)>,B\<in\>Form<around*|(|\<cal*-L\><rsup|p>|)>.>

    A \<equiv\> B if and only if both A \<vDash\> B and B \<vDash\> A.
  </theorem>

  <\proof>
    \;

    Sufficiency:

    <math|A\<equiv\>B\<Rightarrow\>A<rsup|v>=B<rsup|v>> for every valuation v;

    then if <math|A<rsup|v>=1,B<rsup|v>=1,that is A\<vDash\>B,and vise versa.>

    Necessarity:

    if <math|A\<vDash\>B,then <around*|(|A<rsup|v>=1|)>\<rightarrow\><around*|(|B<rsup|v>=1|)>>

    if <math|B\<vDash\>A,if A<rsup|v>=0,then B<rsup|v> can<rprime|'>t> be 1, so <math|B<rsup|v>=0>.

    Combine each we get <math|A\<equiv\>B>\ 

    \;
  </proof>

  <\theorem>
    Empty set

    Suppose <math|A\<in\>Form<around*|(|\<cal*-L\><rsup|p>|)>.>

    <math|\<varnothing\>\<vDash\>A means that A is tautology.>
  </theorem>

  <\proof>
    \;

    <math|We define for every v,\<varnothing\><rsup|v>=1>

    So if <math|\<varnothing\>\<vDash\>A> means that for every v,<math|A<rsup|v>=1>,

    Which means A is tautology.

    \;
  </proof>

  <\theorem>
    Semantic Entailment\ 

    Suppose <math|A\<in\>Form<around*|(|\<cal*-L\><rsup|p>|)>,B\<in\>Form<around*|(|\<cal*-L\><rsup|p>|)>.>

    A \<vDash\> B if and only if A \<rightarrow\> B is tautology.
  </theorem>

  If <math|A\<in\>Form<around*|(|\<cal*-L\><rsup|p>|)>,B\<in\>Form<around*|(|\<cal*-L\><rsup|p>|)>>, then the proposition is obvious. We omit the prove.

  \;

  <\theorem>
    Semantic Entailment语义蕴含

    <math|<around*|{|A<rsub|1>,A<rsub|2>,\<ldots\>A<rsub|n>|}>\<vDash\>A >if and only if <math|\<varnothing\>\<vDash\>A<rsub|1>\<wedge\>\<cdots\>\<wedge\>A<rsub|n>\<rightarrow\>A>.
  </theorem>

  Since <math|A<rsub|i>\<in\>Form<around*|(|\<cal*-L\><rsup|p>|)>,A\<in\>Form<around*|(|\<cal*-L\><rsup|p>|)>>, the two propositions have the same meanings.

  \;

  <section|N-ary Boolean Functions>

  <subsection|Definition>

  To generalize, n-ary logical connectives are n-ary Boolean Functions (n 元布尔函数),\ 

  which takes n boolean inputs and returns a single boolean output.

  <\align>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|f:<around*|{|T,F|}><rsup|n>\<rightarrow\><around*|{|T,F|}>>|<cell|,n\<in\>\<bbb-N\>>>>>
  </align>

  <subsection|Possibilities of n-ary Function>

  For a n-ary function, there are n input values, so there are <math|2<rsup|n>> different kinds of cases of inputs.

  And 2 different outputs to each input, form <math|2<rsup|2<rsup|n>>> different n-ary boolean funcions.

  \;

